Plum's Stage
London —— Facing Theresa May, the new UK Prime Minister, is a daunting task: implementing the wishes of British voters — or, more precisely, those of England and Wales — to "leave the EU," and managing the far-reaching consequences of this endeavor.
This challenge she faces dwarfs those of her predecessors in recent years.
But she may have the capability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like Chancellor Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to accomplish the task are in May's hands.
She is smart and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology and is very adept at exercising control, operating within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
May won in most of the battles she participated in and showed no mercy to those who had used underhand means against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to fully leverage it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The UK's Brexit process has already begun, beyond doubt.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the result of the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers agree with her.
But May has yet to provide a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely challenging to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It's difficult to know precisely what you will actually be eating.
A Northern Ireland "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Based on your surroundings and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various combinations.
The same applies to Brexit for the UK.
Some may primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Some may be more concerned with obtaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality that Brexit supporters often overlook is that the EU will not give Britain any benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to punish the UK or because of any attempt to undermine the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric, like Boris Johnson, the UK's new Foreign Secretary, calling it "Hitlerian imperialism").
Instead, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge over the coming months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be in the difficult negotiations to come regarding its relationship with the EU (and, in terms of trade, the world) based on reality.
Given the scope of the agenda (there are at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(My granddaughter, who will be 11 years old when the negotiations are completed, might already be starting university!)
) We must prioritize to prevent the negotiations from dragging on for even longer.
The goal is to achieve a balance between allowing British exports of goods and services (especially financial services) into other European countries and restricting EU citizens from entering the UK.
The more concessions negotiators make in one area, the greater the compromises they need to accept in others.
May needs to fully leverage her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation outcomes.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that the discontented are not just a part – such a result is inevitable – but all.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing divide in British society exposed by the UK's withdrawal from the EU.
Blue-collar workers in England's north and midlands were the main force behind the UK's Brexit referendum, long distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called globalizers – the EU.
Metropolitan areas in England – especially London – may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not received any advantages.
Due to a lack of confidence in the left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party he leads, many blue-collar workers ultimately fell prey to the Brexit-populist promises.
"They will reverse globalization," they said.
"They will expel immigrants depressing wages and redirect millions of pounds that would otherwise go to the EU towards public services."
They promised that Brexit would return the UK to a safer and more prosperous past.
Leavers cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can immigration from the EU be cut off.
Any such move would ruin British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, workers who voted for Brexit may still become disheartened, finding that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and the pressure on public services persists.
This is unlikely to boost social cohesion.
The UK's Brexit referendum has unleashed an uncontrollable populist情绪风暴emotional storm.
Just like Donald Trump's inability to improve the circumstances of American blue-collar voters, no matter how things appear, Brexit cannot bring any benefits to those who chose it.
Despite these advantages, such challenges may still prove difficult for May to overcome.
